content:
This chunk provides an example of setting up a linear fog node in both Python and C++ within the context of implementing fog effects in computer graphics. The code demonstrates how to create a linear fog effect by specifying color, range, fallback parameters, attaching the fog node to the render tree, and applying it to the scene. This is part of the broader discussion on implementing fog effects, including different modes (linear vs. exponential) and their respective configurations.

Setup a linear fog node at the origin:

python

color = (0.5, 0.8, 0.8)
linfog = Fog("A linear-mode Fog node")
linfog.setColor(*color)
linfog.setLinearRange(0, 320)
linfog.setLinearFallback(45, 160, 320)
render.attachNewNode(linfog)
render.setFog(linfog)

cpp

LColor color(0.5,0.8,0.8);
PT(Fog) linfog = new Fog("A linear-mode Fog node");
linfog->set_color(color);
linfog->set_linear_range(0, 320);
linfog->set_linear_fallback(45, 160, 320);
render.attach_new_node(linfog);
render.set_fog(linfog);
